        // === THEORY ===
        theory(1, "Population & Social Issues",
            "Define 'marriage' in the context of Ghanaian society.\nState four reasons that will cause you to marry when the time is due.\nSuggest four possible reasons for the longevity (long survival) of a marriage.",
            "(a) Definition of Marriage:\nIn Ghanaian society, marriage is a legally, socially, and traditionally recognized union between a man and a woman, established through customary rites, religious ordinances, or civil registry, to live together as husband and wife and build a family.\n\n(b) Four reasons to marry when the time is due:\n1. Procreation: To give birth to children and ensure the continuation of the family name.\n2. Companionship: To have a life partner for emotional support, love, and friendship.\n3. Social Status: To gain respect and maturity recognition in the community.\n4. Cultural/Religious Fulfillment: To obey custom obligations and religious teachings on family life.\n\n(c) Four reasons for longevity in marriage:\n1. Mutual Trust and Honesty: Openness and faithfulness prevent suspicion and build strong family bonds.\n2. Effective Communication: Calmly discussing feelings and challenges helps resolve misunderstandings early.\n3. Patience and Forgiveness: Recognizing human imperfections and forgiving wrongs prevents accumulation of resentment.\n4. Financial Transparency: Honestly sharing income details and planning household budgets together reduces financial arguments.",
            "Marriage definition: 4 Marks\n4 Reasons to marry: 4 Marks\n4 Longevity keys: 12 Marks\nTotal: 20 Marks", 20),

        theory(2, "Government & Citizenship",
            "Explain the term 'Human Rights'.\nIdentify two common human rights abuses in your community.\nSuggest four reasons why society must be educated on Human Rights.",
            "(a) (i) Explanation of Human Rights:\nHuman Rights are the fundamental rights, moral freedoms, and entitlements that every individual is born with, regardless of nationality, sex, ethnicity, religion, or social status. They are guaranteed by the national constitution to protect human dignity.\n\n(ii) Two common human rights abuses:\n1. Child Labour: Forcing young children to perform dangerous work like galamsey mining, commercial fishing, or street hawking.\n2. Domestic Violence: Inflicting physical abuse, beatings, or verbal assaults on spouses or children inside the household.\n\n(b) Four reasons why society must be educated on Human Rights:\n1. Abuse Prevention: Educating people helps them recognize when their rights are being violated so they can seek legal redress.\n2. Promote Equality and Respect: Fosters tolerance and stops discrimination based on gender, tribe, or physical disability.\n3. Protecting Vulnerable Groups: Defends children, widows, and people with disabilities from traditional or family maltreatment.\n4. Hold Authority Accountable: Empowers citizens to demand fair treatment and justice from security agencies and state officials.",
            "Human Rights explanation: 4 Marks\n2 Abuses listing: 4 Marks\n4 Reasons for education: 12 Marks\nTotal: 20 Marks", 20),

        theory(3, "Government & Citizenship",
            "Explain the term 'Constitution'.\nList four important reasons why Ghana decided to practice a republican system of government.\nState three points on how the 1992 Constitution contributes to the development of the nation.",
            "(a) Explanation of Constitution:\nA constitution is the supreme body of laws, rules, principles, and legal frameworks that outlines how a country must be governed, detailing the structures of state organs and protecting the rights and duties of its citizens.\n\n(b) Four reasons why Ghana adopted a republican system:\n1. Full Sovereignty: To ensure the Head of State is a Ghanaian citizen, fully removing the British monarch as the ceremonial head.\n2. Representative Democracy: The President and Parliament are directly elected by the citizens, giving power to the grassroot people.\n3. Equal Civic Rights: A republic ensures all citizens are equal before the law, with no hereditary royal privileges in state governance.\n4. National Identity: Solidifies Ghana as an independent, self-governing African state on the global stage.\n\n(c) Three contributions of the 1992 Constitution to development:\n1. Political Stability: It has guaranteed peaceful transitions of power since 1993, creating a stable atmosphere for businesses to grow.\n2. Protection of Rights: Protects speech, media, and enterprise, enabling citizens to innovate and speak freely.\n3. Decentralization: It mandates the creation of local District Assemblies, bringing governance and development projects closer to rural communities.",
            "Constitution explanation: 4 Marks\n4 Republican reasons: 4 Marks\n3 Development contributions: 12 Marks\nTotal: 20 Marks", 20),

        theory(4, "History & Colonization",
            "Identify four major factors that led to the 1948 riots in the Gold Coast.\nHighlight four ways in which the 1948 riots contributed to Ghana's struggle for independence.",
            "(a) Four factors leading to the 1948 riots:\n1. The Christiansborg Crossroad Shooting: Police Superintendent Imray shot and killed three peaceful ex-servicemen on February 28, 1948.\n2. Extreme Economic Hardships: High cost of living, low wages for local workers, and lack of jobs for returning World War II veterans.\n3. Boycott of European Goods: Organized by Nii Kwabena Bonne III to protest the high prices and monopoly of European merchant shops (AWAM).\n4. Political Frustrations: The Burns Constitution of 1946 failed to give educated Africans meaningful power in the Legislative Council.\n\n(b) Four ways the 1948 riots accelerated Ghana's independence:\n1. Creation of Watson Commission: The riots forced the British to set up a commission which declared the Burns Constitution outdated and recommended self-rule.\n2. Birth of Coussey Committee: This led directly to a committee of Africans drafting a new constitution, laying the legal path to elections.\n3. UGCC Arrests (The Big Six): The arrest of Danquah, Nkrumah, and others made them national heroes, uniting the country behind them.\n4. Split and CPP Formation: The fast political pace encouraged Nkrumah to form the CPP, mobilizing the masses for 'Self-Government Now'.",
            "4 Causes of riots: 8 Marks\n4 Contributions to independence: 12 Marks\nTotal: 20 Marks", 20),

        theory(5, "Economy & Development",
            "Explain the concept of 'Social Security' to your parents.\nState any two national Social Security Schemes available in Ghana.\nSuggest four reasons to convince an individual to join a Social Security Scheme in Ghana.",
            "(a) (i) Concept of Social Security:\nSocial Security is a state-regulated public insurance program designed to provide financial protection and monthly income support to workers and their families when they retire, become disabled, or pass away.\n\n(ii) Two national Social Security Schemes in Ghana:\n1. SSNIT Tier 1 Pension Scheme (Basic National Social Security Scheme).\n2. Tier 2 Occupational Pension Scheme (Mandatory fully-funded scheme managed by private trusts).\n\n(b) Four reasons to join a Social Security Scheme:\n1. Old Age Financial Security: Guarantees a stable, monthly pension income after retirement, avoiding financial dependence on children.\n2. Invalidity Benefits: Provides financial support to the contributor if they suffer a permanent disability or illness before retirement.\n3. Survivor's Livelihood: Pays out a lump sum benefit to the registered dependents or family of the worker if they pass away.\n4. Access to Free NHIS: Pensioners under SSNIT enjoy free registration and membership renewals under the National Health Insurance Scheme.",
            "Social Security concept: 4 Marks\n2 National Schemes: 4 Marks\n4 Benefits to convince: 12 Marks\nTotal: 20 Marks", 20)
